<main class="page">

  <!-- ════════════ LORE ════════════ -->
  <div id="lore" class="lore-intro">
    In the villages of Lombok, the word <em>selak</em> carries the weight of a moral fall — derived from <em>salak</em>, meaning "wrong" or "mistaken," it names the art of those whose intentions went astray and who gained something terrible in exchange. The tuselak is a shapeshifter, a predator, a sorcerer who walks between the human and the monstrous. But the oldest stories remember that this was not always an art of malice. Before it became a weapon of cruelty, <em>ilmu selak</em> was a warrior's shield — a way to test one's strength against the darkness by becoming it.
  </div>
  <div class="lore-intro" style="padding-top:0;">
    Druids of the Circle of the Selak walk that original, razor-thin line. They draw on the same primal current that creates monsters — the forbidden knowledge called <em>ilmu hitam</em> — but channel it through the discipline of the druidic tradition. Their transformations are imperfect and uncanny: beast-shapes that retain human hands, spectral forms that trail green phosphorescence, presences that radiate an almost physical dread. They are healers who smell of decay, protectors whose methods terrify the people they defend. The communities they serve may never fully trust them, because the knowledge that fights the tuselak and the knowledge that <em>creates</em> the tuselak are, as the Sasak say, inseparable.
  </div>

  <div class="divider">· · ·</div>

  <!-- ════════════ CIRCLE SPELLS ════════════ -->
  <section id="spells">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>Circle Spells</h2>
      <span class="level-tag">3rd-Level Circle of the Selak Feature</span>
    </div>
    <div class="rules-text">
      <p>Your connection to the selak tradition grants you access to certain spells. When you reach a Druid level specified in the table below, you thereafter always have the listed spells prepared.</p>
    </div>
    <table class="spell-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Druid Level</th><th>Spells</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>3</td><td>Hex, Disguise Self</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5</td><td>Blindness/Deafness, Phantasmal Force</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7</td><td>Fear, Bestow Curse</td></tr>
        <tr><td>9</td><td>Greater Invisibility, Phantasmal Killer</td></tr>
        <tr><td>13</td><td>Dominate Person, Mislead</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <div class="divider">· · ·</div>

  <!-- ════════════ SELAK FORM ════════════ -->
  <section id="selak-form">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>Selak Form</h2>
      <span class="level-tag">3rd-Level Circle of the Selak Feature</span>
    </div>
    <div class="rules-text">
      <p>You can channel the shapeshifting art of the <em>selak</em> to assume a form that is neither fully beast nor fully human — an incomplete, uncanny transformation that retains your mind and statistics while wreathing you in predatory power.</p>
      <p>As a <strong>Bonus Action</strong>, you can expend a use of your <strong>Wild Shape</strong> to enter your <strong>Selak Form</strong> rather than transforming into a beast. While in Selak Form, the following rules apply:</p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Duration.</span> The form lasts for 10 minutes. It ends early if you dismiss it (no action required), if you are Incapacitated, or if you use Wild Shape again.</p>
      <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">No Concentration.</span> This feature does not require Concentration. You can maintain a Concentration spell while in Selak Form.</p>
      <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Your Statistics.</span> You retain all of your game statistics. You do not assume a beast's stat block.</p>
      <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Temporary Hit Points.</span> You gain Temporary Hit Points equal to <strong>2 &times; your Druid level</strong> when you enter Selak Form (some aspects override this amount).</p>
      <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">The Green Light.</span> A faint emerald phosphorescence appears on your forehead, dripping downward like luminous sweat. You shed Dim Light in a 10-foot radius. This light cannot be hidden by nonmagical means.</p>
      <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Nocturnal Predator.</span> You have Darkvision out to 60 feet if you don't already have it. Additionally, you have Advantage on Dexterity (Stealth) checks made in dim light or darkness.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="rules-text">When you enter Selak Form, choose one of the following three aspects. You can choose a different aspect each time you enter the form.</p>

    <!-- Ekek -->
    <div class="aspect-card">
      <div class="aspect-card-header">
        <div class="aspect-card-image">
          <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ekek — The Prowler">
        </div>
        <div class="aspect-card-title">
          <h3>Ekek</h3>
          <div class="subtitle">The Prowler</div>
          <div class="role-badge">Melee Striker</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="aspect-card-body">
        <p class="flavor">Your frame hunches and ripples with bestial power. Your fingers end in curved claws, your joints bend at wrong angles, your movements become those of a hunting animal — and yet your human shape persists, grotesquely intact. Human hands. Human feet. An animal that is not an animal.</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Fortified Form.</span> When you enter Selak Form in this aspect, you gain Temporary Hit Points equal to <strong>3 &times; your Druid level</strong>, instead of the normal amount.</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Predator's Strike.</span> When you take the Attack action on your turn, you can make a special melee spell attack in place of one of your attacks. On a hit, the target takes <strong>1d8 + your Wisdom modifier Psychic damage</strong> and can't take Reactions until the start of your next turn. The damage die changes when you reach Druid levels <strong>5</strong> (1d10), <strong>11</strong> (1d12), and <strong>17</strong> (2d6).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Cahaya -->
    <div class="aspect-card">
      <div class="aspect-card-header">
        <div class="aspect-card-image">
          <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Cahaya — The Ghostlight">
        </div>
        <div class="aspect-card-title">
          <h3>Cahaya</h3>
          <div class="subtitle">The Ghostlight</div>
          <div class="role-badge">Ranged Blaster</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="aspect-card-body">
        <p class="flavor">Your outline wavers and blurs, as if seen through the shimmer of heat rising from a rice paddy at midnight. A cold green radiance bleeds from your brow and collects at your fingertips. You become translucent, spectral, wrong — a ball of foxfire wearing a human shape.</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Ghostfire Bolt.</span> As a <strong>Bonus Action</strong>, you can hurl a bolt of spectral green light at one creature you can see within <strong>60 feet</strong>. Make a ranged spell attack. On a hit, the target takes <strong>1d8 + your Wisdom modifier Psychic damage</strong>. The damage die changes when you reach Druid levels <strong>5</strong> (1d10), <strong>11</strong> (1d12), and <strong>17</strong> (2d6).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Bayangan -->
    <div class="aspect-card">
      <div class="aspect-card-header">
        <div class="aspect-card-image">
          <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"aspect-card-title">
        </div>
        <div class="aspect-card-title">
          <h3>Bayangan</h3>
          <div class="subtitle">The Dread</div>
          <div class="role-badge">Drain Tank</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="aspect-card-body">
        <p class="flavor">Your head wrenches free. There is no blood — only a trail of luminous, ropy viscera that dangles beneath you like the roots of an uprooted tree, glowing faintly green and pulsing with a slow, terrible rhythm. Your body crumples behind you as you rise, a floating head haloed in ghostlight, mouth open, eyes wide and unblinking. The stench hits before the fear does — the sweet, cloying rot of waterlogged vegetation, of the tropical earth digesting itself. You are the thing that drifts through open windows at midnight. The thing that feeds.</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Draining Presence.</span> At the start of each of your turns, each creature of your choice within <strong>5 feet</strong> of you must make a <strong>Constitution saving throw</strong> against your spell save DC. On a failure, a creature takes <strong>1d4 + your Wisdom modifier Necrotic damage</strong>. On a success, it takes half as much damage. You gain <strong>Temporary Hit Points equal to half the total damage dealt</strong> by this feature (rounded down, minimum 1). The damage die changes when you reach Druid levels <strong>5</strong> (1d6), <strong>11</strong> (1d8), and <strong>17</strong> (1d10).</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Aura of Dread.</span> When a creature you can see within <strong>30 feet</strong> makes an attack roll, you can use your <strong>Reaction</strong> to force it to make a <strong>Wisdom saving throw</strong> against your spell save DC. On a failure, the creature is <strong>Frightened</strong> of you until the end of its next turn.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider">· · ·</div>

  <!-- ════════════ BEBAI ════════════ -->
  <section id="bebai">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>Bebai — The Unborn Familiar</h2>
      <span class="level-tag">3rd-Level Circle of the Selak Feature</span>
    </div>

    <div class="aspect-card" style="margin-top: 20px;">
      <div class="aspect-card-header">
        <div class="aspect-card-image">
          <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Bebai — The Unborn Familiar">
        </div>
        <div class="aspect-card-title">
          <p class="flavor" style="border-left: none; padding-left: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">A servitor spirit from the Sasak tradition, crafted through dark ritual and bound to its master's will. In folklore, the bebai is a spirit of terrible origin — for your character, it may be inherited, pact-bound, or summoned through means you prefer not to discuss.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="aspect-card-body">
        <div class="rules-text">
          <p>When you use the <strong>Wild Companion</strong> feature (which lets you expend a use of Wild Shape to cast <em>Find Familiar</em>), your familiar takes the form of a <strong>bebai</strong>. It has the statistics of a familiar summoned by <em>Find Familiar</em>, with the following changes:</p>
        </div>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Creature Type.</span> The bebai's creature type is <strong>Undead</strong> rather than Fey. It appears as a Tiny translucent spectral shade — a pale, luminous figure no larger than a cat, trailing wisps of green phosphorescence from hollow eyes.</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Ghostly Veil.</span> As a <strong>Bonus Action</strong>, the bebai can turn <strong>Invisible</strong>. It remains invisible until it attacks, forces a saving throw, or until you dismiss the invisibility (no action required).</p>
        <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Haunt.</span> As a <strong>Bonus Action</strong> on your turn, you can command the bebai to haunt a creature within <strong>10 feet</strong> of it. The target must succeed on a <strong>Wisdom saving throw</strong> against your spell save DC or have <strong>Disadvantage on the next saving throw</strong> it makes within the next minute. The bebai can use this feature a number of times equal to <strong>half your Druid level (rounded up)</strong>, and it regains all expended uses when you finish a <strong>Long Rest</strong>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider">· · ·</div>

  <!-- ════════════ SENTULAK ════════════ -->
  <section id="sentulak">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>Sentulak — The Returning</h2>
      <span class="level-tag">6th-Level Circle of the Selak Feature</span>
    </div>
    <div class="rules-text">
      <p>You master the counter-art of <em>sentulak</em> — literally "returning the selak" — the discipline of reflecting hostile magic back upon its source. In the Sasak tradition, <em>sentulak</em> is classified as <em>ilmu putih</em> (white knowledge), a defensive art specifically designed to turn a sorcerer's own power against them.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Warded Mind.</span> You have <strong>Advantage on saving throws against being Charmed or Frightened</strong>. You have internalized the counter-art: the dread and manipulation that the selak tradition deals in can no longer easily be turned against you.</p>
    <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Reflect the Selak.</span> While in <strong>Selak Form</strong>, when you <strong>succeed on a saving throw</strong> against an effect caused by a creature you can see within 60 feet, you can use your <strong>Reaction</strong> to psychically lash the source. That creature takes <strong>2d8 Psychic damage</strong> and has <strong>Disadvantage on the next attack roll or saving throw it makes before the end of your next turn</strong>. You can use this Reaction a number of times equal to your <strong>Wisdom modifier</strong> (minimum of once), and you regain all expended uses when you finish a <strong>Long Rest</strong>.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="divider">· · ·</div>

  <!-- ════════════ ILMU NENGKESUR ════════════ -->
  <section id="nengkesur">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>Ilmu Nengkesur — The Art of Flight</h2>
      <span class="level-tag">10th-Level Circle of the Selak Feature</span>
    </div>
    <div class="rules-text">
      <p>You unlock <em>ilmu nengkesur</em>, the art of flight recognized in the Sasak tradition as one of the highest expressions of supernatural mastery.</p>
      <p>While in <strong>Selak Form</strong>, you gain the following benefits:</p>
    </div>
    <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Flight.</span> You have a <strong>Fly Speed of 30 feet</strong> and can <strong>hover</strong>.</p>
    <p class="feature-item"><span class="fname">Resistance.</span> You have <strong>Resistance to Necrotic and Psychic damage</strong>.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="divider">· · ·</div>

  <!-- ════════════ CAPSTONE ════════════ -->
  <section id="capstone">
    <div class="section-header">
      <h2>Selaq Mate Ndek — The Undying Selak</h2>
      <span class="level-tag">14th-Level Circle of the Selak Feature</span>
    </div>

    <div class="capstone-quote">
      "Tuselak never die."
      <cite>— Amaq Bahar, shaman of Western Lombok</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-text">
      <p>When you are in <strong>Selak Form</strong> and <strong>drop to 0 hit points</strong>, you can use your <strong>Reaction</strong> to refuse death. Instead of falling Unconscious, you drop to a number of hit points equal to <strong>2 &times; your Druid level</strong>, and you release a psychic shockwave of pure dread. Each creature of your choice that you can see within <strong>30 feet</strong> must make a <strong>Wisdom saving throw</strong> against your spell save DC. On a failed save, a creature takes <strong>3d10 Psychic damage</strong> and is <strong>Frightened</strong> of you for 1 minute. On a successful save, a creature takes half as much damage and isn't Frightened. A Frightened creature can repeat the saving throw at the end of each of its turns, ending the effect on itself on a success.</p>
      <p>Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a <strong>Long Rest</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

